    "source_image": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/4/49/Rhithrogena_germanica_subimago_on_Equisetum_hyemale.jpg",
    "commons_title": "File:Rhithrogena germanica subimago on Equisetum hyemale.jpg",
    "description": "A female subimago of March Brown (Rhithrogena germanica) mayfly in the family Heptageniidae. Mayflies are insects which belong to the Order Ephemeroptera (from the Greek ephemeros, short-lived and pteron, wing, referring to the short life span of adults). They have been placed into an ancient group of insects termed the Paleoptera, which also contains the dragonflies and damselflies. They are aquatic insects whose immature stage (called naiad or, colloquially, nymph) usually lasts one year in fresh water. It is resting on a Rough Horsetail Equisetum hyemale stem.",
    "artist": "Richard Bartz, Munich aka Makro Freak Image:MFB.jpg",
    "credit": "Own work",
    "license": "CC BY-SA 2.5",
    "license_url": "https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/2.5"
  },
  {
    "kind": "insect",
    "group": "mayfly",
    "stage": "egg",
    "label": "Mayfly eggs",
    "query": "mayfly eggs",
    "file": "/Users/paulmccallick/Documents/flyPatterns/images/insects/mayfly/egg/mayfly-egg.jpg",
    "source_page": "https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Mayfly_at_Seedskadee_National_Wildlife_Refuge_(49868056532).jpg",
    "source_image": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/2/26/Mayfly_at_Seedskadee_National_Wildlife_Refuge_%2849868056532%29.jpg",
    "commons_title": "File:Mayfly at Seedskadee National Wildlife Refuge (49868056532).jpg",
    "description": "Small mayfly species are abundant in the Green River at Seedskadee National Wildlife. The life cycle of these small mayflies is spent mostly on the bottom of the river in highly oxygenated water in the nymphal stage. For a brief few days in the spring and again in the fall, the nymph rises to the surface, sheds its exoskeleton, inflates its wings, joins a swarm of others, mates, and falls back to the river to die. The female deposits the fertilized eggs on the river bottom and the life cycle starts again. In addition to feeding trout and other fish, migratory birds eat a lot of adult mayflies as well. They are available to birds as flying/mating adults in the spring, and again in the fall, when most other insects are scarce due to cool temperatures. Refuge. Photo: Tom Koerner/U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service",
    "artist": "USFWS Mountain Prairie",
    "credit": "Mayfly at Seedskadee National Wildlife Refuge",
    "license": "Public domain",
    "license_url": ""
  },
